111
00:09:06.329 --> 00:09:10.881
And the final takeaway from our visit
to the Yale collection of musical

112
00:09:10.881 --> 00:09:15.509
instruments, in the first 100 years
of the existence of the piano,

113
00:09:15.509 --> 00:09:21.470
from its invention in 1700 to the piano of
around 1800, not all that much changed.

114
00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:28.720
But during the next 60 years or so,
up to the Steinway of 1867 that we saw,

115
00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:33.700
the piano changed enormously,
going from an almost tiny toy with limited

116
00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:39.620
sound to a monster of various colors and
huge sound.

117
00:09:39.620 --> 00:09:45.414
Notice of course that all this happened
during what period in Western history?

118
00:09:47.854 --> 00:09:53.402
Well, the Industrial Revolution
in Europe and America.

119
00:09:53.402 --> 00:09:59.718
For the piano, the great age of change
was the 60 years between 1800 and 1860.

120
00:09:59.718 --> 00:10:04.820
And not much has changed on
the concert grand since then.

121
00:10:04.820 --> 00:10:07.640
The Industrial Revolution
with the piano and

122
00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:12.850
with other musical instruments,
as we'll see, was the first great era

123
00:10:12.850 --> 00:10:17.650
of technological change in
Western musical history.

124
00:10:19.030 --> 00:10:23.030
The second great change of
technological advance came

125
00:10:23.030 --> 00:10:27.350
during the 20th century with
the popularization of recorded music.

126
00:10:27.350 --> 00:10:32.090
And then especially with a capacity to
digitalize recorded sound to the point

127
00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:38.230
that the entire world of music can
now be contained in a phone and

128
00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:39.600
held in your hand.

129
00:10:41.300 --> 00:10:42.973
Now that's real change.